    "Finally, other option is to rescale each of the images of the original MNIST dataset (in this work, represented by block 3).",
    "For example, if our crossbar has 64 inputs, then the image would have to be rescaled from 28 × 28 to 8 × 8 (i.e., 64 pixels); the size of the rescaled image will be referred as n×n.",
    "The rescaling can be easily done via software, using for example MATLAB and its Deep Learning Toolbox as language/platform to carry out this type of computational operations, or Python altogether with the TensorFlow, Keras or Pytorch libraries.",
    "However, and as shown in Fig. 4b, the aggressively rescaled images becomes barely readable and therefore the entire dataset is changed and so it is the benchmark, i.e.",
    "inference results obtained for the 8×8 MNIST rescaled images should only be compared with 8×8 MNIST results and not with the original MNIST benchmark results."
